[`onig_init()`](https://github.com/k-takata/Onigmo/blob/8bd7e1863ff0f5b80353f3cc3d8944a6dfb6f44d/regcomp.c#L5960) is not thread safe.

``` c
extern int
onig_init(void)
{
  if (onig_inited != 0)
    return 0;

  THREAD_SYSTEM_INIT;
  THREAD_ATOMIC_START;

  onig_inited = 1;
```

The above block is not an atomic block, so `THREAD_SYSTEM_INIT` might be called more than once.

This may cause problems when calling `onig_new()` from multiple threads without calling `onig_init()` explicitly. [doc/API](https://github.com/k-takata/Onigmo/blob/8bd7e1863ff0f5b80353f3cc3d8944a6dfb6f44d/doc/API#L10) says:

> You don't have to call it explicitly, because it is called in onig_new().

But it's not true when calling `onig_new()` from multiple threads.
A workaround is calling `onig_init()` explicitly (from the main thread) before calling `onig_new()`.

